Red Wine Quality Exploratory Data Analysis by Lam Raga A. Markely

This dataset contains information about various red wine samples with their chemical properties and quality. The goal of the analysis is to identify which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines.

The red wine dataset consists of 12 features, including 11 input variables (fixed.acidity to alcohol), 1 output variable (quality), and 1599 samples. The feature X is the index of the dataset. The definition of the variables are described in detail here. In the following analysis, the variable fixed acidity will be referred as tartaric acid, volatile acidity as acetic acid, chlorides as sodium chloride, and sulphates as potassium sulphate as described in the above link.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 wine samples with 11 features: tartaric acid concentration, acetic acid concentration, citric acid concentration, residual sugar concentration, sodium chloride concentration, free sulfur dioxide concentration, total sulfur dioxide concentration, density, pH, potassium sulphate concentration, % alcohol, and quality. All of the features are continuous variables. Some of the feature distributions are close to normal, while others are skewed to the right. The wine quality is a score between 0 and 10.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The feature of interest is the quality of the wine. This analysis aims to investigate which of the other features influence the quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

All the features are related with the chemical composition, chemical property, and physical property of the wine sample. So, I suspect each feature will have some influence on the quality, although some features may have more influence than the others.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

There are 3 new variables created: 1. Total acid concentration: tartaric acid + acetic acid + citric acid concentration 2. Total salt concentration: sodium chloride concentration + potassium sulphate concentration 3. Dioxide ratio: free sulfur dioxide concentration/total sulfur dioxide concentration

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Some of the features are skewed and have 0 values. However, no transformation was performed as these values are reasonable and will be used as input variables in regression later.
